  "response": "To determine the wing size for human flight, we need to consider several factors:\n\n1. Human weight:\n- An average adult human weighs approximately 70-80 kg (154-176 lbs)\n\n2. Wing size calculation:\n- Using principles from bird and aircraft wing design, wings would need to be significantly large\n- Estimated wingspan required: Around 6.1-7.3 meters (20-24 feet) wide\n- Wing surface area would need to be approximately 4-5 square meters\n\n3. Structural considerations:\n- Wings would require extremely powerful chest and shoulder muscles\n- Bones would need to be hollow and lightweight, similar to bird anatomy\n- Significant metabolic changes to support flight energy requirements\n\n4. Practical limitations:\n- Such large wings would make ground movement difficult\n- The weight and muscle mass required would make sustained flight challenging\n- Humans lack the lightweight bone structure of birds\n\n5. Comparative biology:\n- Large flying birds like condors have wingspans of 3-3.3 meters\n- Human flight would require proportionally larger wings due to higher body mass\n\nWhile theoretically possible, human-powered flight with wings would be extremely impractical and physiologically demanding.",
